liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Earlier, we shared the World Health Organization's update in Al-Shifa hospital. Now, the United Nation's Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs estimates some 3,000 patients remain trapped in the hospital. They say two premature babies and 10 other patients have died since the power outage that started on November 11. The organisation also claim s three nurses have been killed and an estimated 15,000 displaced people remain in the hospital. Critical infrastructure including the oxygen station, water tanks, a cardiovascular facility and the maternity ward was damaged, the UN's office says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Two babies, 10 patients dead in al-Shifa hospital: UN update

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Brisbane protester Sameer was among thousands of Australians rallying this weekend either in support of Palestinian communities or Israeli ones. The proud Australian Palestinian says his siblings, cousins and other family members — including young children — all live in Gaza. He doesn't know whether they are alive or dead. "Many Palestinians here are going through the same pain like me," he says. "I am here to speak on [my family's] behalf, to tell our Australian government enough is enough, call for a ceasefire." In a separate Israeli rally, Shaina — whose grandparents were holocaust survivors — says the Jewish community is hurting. "Obviously I'm not going through what they're going through, but the sentiment is there," Shaina says. "For them and for a lot of Jewish people, this is a second Holocaust." Read the full story here:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The daughter of the only Australian to be killed in Hamas's terrorist attack on southern Israel says she will never see her mother's "beautiful smile" again. Galit Carbone was residing in an Israeli kibbutz near the Gaza border when Hamas stormed into her house and killed her on October 7. Now, daughter Nicole has returned to the scene of the massacre with ABC reporter Allyson Horn. "The bad guys that actually killed my mum, they've been in here, in my house, in my room," Nicole says. "She was everything to me. She was my best friend. "I never realised they were going to take away my mum. "I'm not going to see her good eyes again, beautiful smile." Watch the full video below:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'She was everything to me': Daughter of Israeli Australian killed by Hamas tells ABC

But ANZ's boss Shayne Elliott says while the bank has profited from higher rates, a surprisingly small number of customers are in mortgage stress. He's told the ABC's senior business correspondent Peter Ryan that of a million borrowers, only 2,000 are seeking help with their repayments — but acknowledged the ANZ may have to help in the coming months. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The ASX has edged lower at lunch time, down 0.2% to 6,965 points as of 12:25pm AEDT. (For live figures at any time, head to the top of the blog.) It's a mixed bag across the sectors, but technology and financials are leading the loss — which can be attributed to two main developments. The tech drop is mostly the result of TPG Telecom ending talks with Vocus over the sale of some of its fibre assets for around $6.3 billion, sending TPG's stocks lower as a result. As for the financials — that's largely because of ANZ's $7.1 billion profit missing market expectations. The sectors that are in the red include: technology (-1.1%), financials (-0.4%), consumer cyclicals (-0.2%), energy (-0.2%) academic and educational services (-0.1%) and real estate (-0.1%). But there's some positive gains for utilities (+0.3%), basic materials (+0.3%), c onsumer non-cyclicals (+0.2%) and industrials (+0.1%). Healthcare is flat. As for the top performers: Elders +15.1% Boral +6.7% NIB +3.55 AUB Group +3.2% Light & Wonder +2.9% And the bottom performers: TPG Telecom -10.2% Chalice Mining -5.5% Weebit Nano -3.9% ANZ -3.5% Domino's Pizza -3%

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Here's more from my colleague David Chau, who has spent his morning at the UBS conference in Sydney : Inflation has proven to be more entrenched than initially expected, and bringing these cost-of-living pressures down will likely be a "bumpy" and "drawn out" process, a senior Reserve Bank official has warned. Although inflation is expected to slow in the months ahead, it is unlikely to fall to 3% (the top of the Reserve Bank's inflation target) until the end of 2025, the RBA assistant governor Marion Kohler told an audience at the UBS Australasia conference in Sydney. "We now expect this to be a more gradual process than we previously thought, due to the still-high level of domestic demand and strong labour and other cost pressures," she said. Ms Kohler (the acting head of the RBA's economics department) also said that s trong domestic demand has led to services inflation remaining higher than expected. "Still-strong levels of demand have allowed businesses to pass on cost increases to customers," Ms Kohler said. "Wages growth has also picked up over the past year, but now appears to have broadly stabilised and is forecast to decline gradually over the next couple of years. "The next stage in bringing inflation back to target is likely to be more drawn out than the first. This has been the experience of some other advanced economies that have been a little ahead of Australia in this inflation cycle." She also said: "The recent increase in fuel prices is also a timely reminder that upside surprises from supply shocks could affect headline inflation. All to say, the road ahead could be bumpy. "
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: RBA official warns of 'bumpy' road ahead to bring inflation down
